Purpose

Determine how experience in everyday activities affects spatial ability, activity experience, looking closely at video game experience. Small scale spatial tasks include the Mental Rotation Task - Shepard and Metzler (MRT), Paper Folding, and Object Assembly. Lastly we look at large scale tasks such as immersive Virtual Reality paradigms such as Dual Solutions Paradigm (DSP) using absolute pointing error and wayfinding efficiency, and a Maze task; a desktop task called Virtual SILCton measured in absolute pointing error within and between routes calculated in z-scores, and a desktop Route Learning task. Questionaires measuring everyday experience and general intelligence included here are the SoCal Spatial Activities Questionaire (SoCalSAQ), a video game experience questionnaire, and Ravens Progressive Matrices (RPM).

#reverse score columns
columns_to_reverse_scores <- c("DSPabs", "DSPineff", "mazeAbs", 
                            "mazeGraphIneff", "mrtRT", "SILCwithinabs", 
                            "SILCbetweenabs", "route")

# Reverse the scores in the selected columns
standardDf[columns_to_reverse_scores] <- -1 * standardDf[columns_to_reverse_scores]
# Step 1: Average DSPabs and DSPineff and save the result as DSP_combined
standardDf$DSP_combined <- (standardDf$DSPabs + standardDf$DSPineff) / 2

# Step 2: Average mazeAbs and mazeGraphIneff and save the result as maze_combined
standardDf$maze_combined <- (standardDf$mazeAbs + standardDf$mazeGraphIneff) / 2

# Step 3: Average pointing errors for SILCton and SILCbetweenabs and save the result as SILC_combined
standardDf$SILC_combined <- rowMeans(standardDf[, c("SILCwithinabs", "SILCbetweenabs")], na.rm = TRUE) / 2
